3\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03ad\u03c1\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd|url=https://www.iefimerida.gr/ellada/koronoios-poios-einai-o-loimoxiologos-sotiris-tsiodras-poy-kerdise-tin-empistosyni-ton|language=Greek|trans-title=Coronavirus: Who is the Greek infectiologist who has won the trust of Greeks|workI Efimerida |location=Athens|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Medical career==\nTsiodras was appointed at the [https://401gsn.army.gr/ 401 Military Hospital] in 1993 where he served for one year. During the years 1994-1997, he worked as an internal medicine specialist specializing in [[Pathology]] at the [[Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia|Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia]] in the United States. From 1997 to 2001, he enrolled in the programs for [[infectious diseases]] at the [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] and [[Harvard Medical School]]. Between 1998 and 2001, he worked as a [[research fellow]] at the Harvard Medical School, from which, in June 2001, he received a [[Medical Sciences]] [[Master's Degree|M.A]].<ref name=studies>{{cite news  |date=24 March 2020 |title=Sydney-born immunologist Sotiris Tsiodras, the \u2018voice\u2019 of coronavirus in Greece|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/161116/sydney-born-immunologist-sotiris-tsiodras-the-voice-of-coronavirus-in-greece/ |work=New World |location= Australia|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he defended his [[doctoral dissertation]] ''[[cum laude]]'' at the Medical School of the National and Kapodistrian University of Athens, titled \"<ref name=dissertation>{{cite web |url=https://www.didaktorika.gr/eadd/handle/10442/13581|title=Effect of protease inhibitors on the metabolic syndrome of patients with HIV infection|last1=Tsiodras |first1=Sotiris |place=